          "line_ref": "L42"
        }
      ],
      "caveat": "Stellar variability and instrument systematics can bias weak spectral features, and degeneracies with cloud properties remain"
    },
    {
      "claim_id": "C04",
      "claim": "Atmosphere-bearing models provide a better joint fit to phase curve and spectrum than no-atmosphere models",
      "strength": "strong",
      "evidence": [
        {
          "quote": "Joint fit likelihood ratio (atmosphere vs no atmosphere): 7.4",
          "line_ref": "L31"
        },
        {
          "quote": "Joint constraints from phase curve and spectrum are stronger than either observable alone",
          "line_ref": "L43"
        }
      ],
      "caveat": "Retrieval assumptions including circulation, opacity priors, and cloud treatment affect quantitative posteriors"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "headline": "JWST finds evidence that TRAPPIST-1 b likely has an atmosphere",
  "plain_language_summary": "TRAPPIST-1 b is a rocky planet about the size of Earth orbiting very close to its small, cool star. Because it is so close, scientists wondered if it still has any atmosphere left or if stellar radiation has stripped it bare. Using NASA's James Webb Space Telescope, researchers measured how the planet's brightness changes as it orbits its star (called a phase curve) and analyzed its infrared light spectrum. They found that the planet shows signs of heat being transported from its day side to its night side, and they detected subtle spectral features consistent with carbon dioxide absorption. These observations favor models that include an atmosphere over models of a bare rock. However, the exact composition, pressure, and extent of the atmosphere remain uncertain and will require additional observations to pin down.",
  "what_is_new": [
    "First phase-curve study of TRAPPIST-1 b using JWST MIRI spectroscopy, combining thermal phase variations with spectral analysis",
    "Evidence for non-zero heat redistribution efficiency (epsilon ~ 0.19) suggesting atmospheric heat transport rather than bare-rock reradiation",
    "Detection of spectral structure near 15 microns consistent with CO2 absorption, providing compositional constraints"
  ],
  "why_caution_is_needed": [
    "This is a single-planet study that cannot be generalized to all rocky planets around M dwarf stars",
    "Retrieval models depend on assumptions about atmospheric circulation, cloud properties, and opacity that affect the quantitative results",
    "Weak spectral features can be affected by stellar variability and instrument systematics, and night-side constraints are weaker than day-side"
  ],
  "glossary": [
    {
      "term": "Phase curve",
      "definition": "A measurement of how a planet's brightness changes over its orbit as different proportions of its day and night sides face the observer"
    },
    {
      "term": "Heat redistribution",
      "definition": "The transport of thermal energy from a planet's hot day side to its cooler night side, typically facilitated by an atmosphere or ocean"
    },
    {
      "term": "MIRI",
      "definition": "Mid-Infrared Instrument on JWST used to measure thermal emission and molecular absorption features in exoplanet atmospheres"
    },
    {
      "term": "Retrieval",
      "definition": "A statistical technique that compares observed data to atmospheric models to infer properties like temperature, composition, and pressure"
    },
    {
      "term": "Tidal locking",
      "definition": "A state where a planet's rotation period matches its orbital period, causing one side to permanently face the star"
    }
  ],
  "open_questions": [
    "What is the exact composition of TRAPPIST-1 b's atmosphere, and could it include gases other than CO2 such as O2?",
    "What is the surface pressure of the atmosphere, and can we distinguish between thin and thick atmospheric scenarios?",
    "Are clouds or hazes present, and how do they affect the thermal emission and spectral interpretation?",
    "How prevalent are atmospheres on rocky planets around M dwarfs, and can these findings be generalized?"
  ]
}
